Hi Phishypro,

The eruption of Mt. Vesuvius nearly 2,000 years ago carbonized a large  
library of ancient scrolls. They were simultaneously destroyed and  
preserved. Researchers believe that new technologies may be able to  
digitally unwrap these scrolls and reveal their contents.

In this competition, you'll build a model to segment the surface of scrolls  
from CT scans, a critical step in virtually unwrapping texts that have  
remained sealed for centuries.

snippet: Hi Phishypro, Every chart, figure and microscope image in a scientific paper tells a story but sometimes, that story is fake. Copy-move forgery, where parts of an image are duplicated to fabricate
body:
Kaggle








Hi Phishypro,

Every chart, figure and microscope image in a scientific paper tells a  
story but sometimes, that story is fake. Copy-move forgery, where parts of  
an image are duplicated to fabricate results, is one of the most common and  
damaging forms of scientific misconduct.

In this competition, you'll build models to detect and segment these  
forgeries in biomedical images. Using a dataset of confirmed forgeries from  
over 2,000 retracted papers, your models will identify duplicated regions  
at the pixel level and help flag tampered images before they spread.





Total Prizes:

$55,000


Entry Deadline:

January 8, 2026




Learn More



Your work could help catch manipulated figures before they're published,  
giving researchers a stronger foundation to build on.

Good luck,

subject: Competition Wrap-Up: Stanford RNA 3D Folding
snippet: Hi Phishypro, The Stanford RNA 3D Folding competition showed what's possible when Kagglers bring creativity, collaboration and data skills to one of biology's toughest puzzles. Participants
body:
Kaggle








Hi Phishypro,

The Stanford RNA 3D Folding competition showed what's possible when  
Kagglers bring creativity, collaboration and data skills to one of  
biology's toughest puzzles.

Participants worked to predict how RNA folds into the 3D shapes that  
determine its function ‚Äî a challenge that has stumped researchers for  
decades. Kagglers made progress that could accelerate breakthroughs in  
medicine and biotechnology.

For the first time, automated methods for RNA 3D structure prediction have  
reached human-competitive performance in blind tests. While many teams  
turned to deep learning, the winning solution by G. John Rao took a  
different path ‚Äî using a handcrafted, highly optimized pipeline that  
revived a classic strategy: template-based modeling.

With over 2,400 submissions, the competition highlighted the power of open  
science. Explore the winning projects to see the wide range of creative  
methods and ideas that emerged.





Learn More




Happy Kaggling!

subject: Competition Launch: CAFA 6 Protein Function Prediction
snippet: Hi Phishypro, Proteins are essential molecules that perform a wide range of functions in all living things. They act as enzymes, provide structure to cells and tissues, support immune defense,
body:
Kaggle








Hi Phishypro,

Proteins are essential molecules that perform a wide range of functions in  
all living things. They act as enzymes, provide structure to cells and  
tissues, support immune defense, transport molecules, and regulate growth,  
repair and energy production. Yet, despite their importance, the functions  
of many proteins remain unknown.

In this competition, you'll build a model to predict the biological  
function of proteins from their amino acid sequences. Using Gene Ontology,  
you'll assign labels that describe what a protein does, the processes it's  
involved in and where it operates within the cell.





Total Prizes:

$50,000


Entry Deadline:

January 26, 2026




Learn More



Your work could help researchers better understand how cells function,  
support the discovery of new treatments and even earn you a spot as a  
co-author on a scientific publication.

Good luck,

body:
Kaggle








Hi Phishypro,

Animal social behavior is intricate and often difficult to  
quantify‚Äîespecially in small mammals like mice. Manual observation is  
time-consuming and inconsistent, and current ML models still struggle to  
generalize across labs and settings.

In this competition, you'll develop ML models to detect and classify 38  
different social and non-social behaviors in co-housed mice using  
markerless motion capture from top-down video. With over 400 hours of  
expertly labeled footage from 20+ recording systems, the dataset challenges  
you to match or exceed the accuracy of human observers across diverse  
environments.





Total Prizes:

$50,000

supporting new discoveries in neuroscience, computational biology and other  
fields.
